@page "/aquaponics"

<section class="aq-hero">
    <h1>What Is Aquaponics?</h1>
    <p>
        Aquaponics is a sustainable farming method that grows fish and plants together in a closed‑loop 
        system. Fish produce nutrient‑rich waste, beneficial bacteria convert that waste into plant 
        fertilizer, and the plants clean the water for the fish.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="aq-section">
    <h2>Why Aquaponics Matters</h2>
    <p>
        Aquaponics uses up to <strong>90% less water</strong> than traditional farming, requires no soil, 
        and produces fresh food year‑round — even during harsh Chicago winters. It’s a climate‑resilient 
        way to grow nutritious food close to the communities that need it most.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="aq-section">
    <h2>Our Fish: Nile Tilapia</h2>
    <p>
        Ripple raises <strong>Nile tilapia</strong>, a hardy freshwater species that thrives in indoor 
        aquaponic systems. Tilapia grow quickly, tolerate a wide range of temperatures and pH levels, 
        and provide a reliable source of protein for local communities.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="aq-section">
    <h2>Our Plants: Buttercrisp Lettuce</h2>
    <p>
        We grow <strong>buttercrisp lettuce</strong>, a leafy green that flourishes in aquaponic 
        conditions. It grows fast, tastes great, and has a long history of success in sustainable 
        indoor farming.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="aq-section">
    <h2>How the System Works</h2>
    <ol class="aq-steps">
        <li><strong>Fish produce waste</strong> — Tilapia release ammonia into the water.</li>
        <li><strong>Bacteria convert the waste</strong> — Ammonia → nitrite → nitrate.</li>
        <li><strong>Plants absorb nutrients</strong> — Lettuce grows in nutrient‑rich water.</li>
        <li><strong>Clean water returns</strong> — Plants filter the water for the fish.</li>
    </ol>
</section>

<section class="aq-section">
    <h2>Why We Chose Aquaponics for Chicago</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Works year‑round</li>
        <li>Thrives indoors</li>
        <li>Uses minimal water</li>
        <li>Produces predictable harvests</li>
        <li>Supports food‑insecure neighborhoods</li>
        <li>Reduces reliance on long‑distance supply chains</li>
    </ul>
</section>
